article.description: Zach Randolph had 27 points and 16 rebounds, and the Portland Trail Blazers returned home after an arduous road trip to beat the Toronto Raptors 105-102 Saturday night.
article.headline: Murray's last-second shot after buzzer
article.linkText: Down 20, Raptors fall just short of Blazers
article.story:
PORTLAND, Ore. (AP) -- After Vince Carter's 3-pointer a week ago foiled the Trail Blazers, Lamond Murray almost did it again to Portland. Murray's 3-pointer at the final buzzer Saturday night appeared to tie the game between the Toronto Raptors and Blazers, but further review by officials showed that the shot was too late. Portland escaped with a 105-102 victory over the rallying Raptors, led by Zach Randolph's 27 points and 16 rebounds. "I was like, `Here we go again," Randolph said of the shot. "But we pulled it out." The Blazers opened a winless three-game road trip in Toronto last Sunday, when Carter hit a go-ahead 3-pointer with 4.8 seconds left in the Raptors' 101-97 victory. "I thought it was good," Murray said. "I thought I got it off in time. But they did the replay and it showed it was still in my fingertips." The Raptors trailed by as many as 20 points in the second half, but Rafer Alston hit the second of consecutive 3-pointers with 2:04 left to give Toronto a brief 100-98 lead. Damon Stoudamire answered with a jumper, and the Blazers led the rest of the way until Murray's shot threw the outcome in momentary doubt. "I was hoping it was late," center Theo Ratliff said. "Then on the monitor I saw the light come on just before it left his hands." Derek Anderson's rim-shaking dunk put the Blazers up 61-51 in the third quarter, the team's biggest lead to that point. Anderson, whose shooting had been off during the trip, also hit a key 3-pointer to make it 66-52. He finished with 19 points. "We stayed faithful to one another and we would finish the game. That's what makes good teams: Staying together and finishing games, regardless of what happens," Anderson said. Alston led the Raptors with 27 points and seven assists. Carter had his lowest point total of the season, with just four in 22 minutes. He made only two of nine shots from the floor and watched from the sideline when the Raptors made their fourth-quarter run. "You've got to put the guys in who were playing well," Carter said. "I'm behind the team in all of their decisions and if that's what they chose to do, that's what I have to deal with." There were eight lead changes in the back-and-forth first half. The Blazers led by as many as seven points, before the Raptors went ahead 23-20 on Murray's 18-foot jumper and a pair of layups. Toronto couldn't extend its lead any further and trailed 48-45 at halftime. The Raptors were coming off an 88-87 loss in Seattle on Friday night. Carter missed a driving reverse layup as time expired. Randolph, the NBA's most improved player last season, has four double-doubles in Portland's first six games.

Game notes
The Blazers signed free agent guard Geno Carlisle to take the roster spot of Richie Frahm, who was placed on the injured list earlier this week with a foot injury. Carlisle was with the Blazers in fall camp, but was waived before the start of the regular season. ... The game was delayed for a few minutes at the start to search for an appropriate game ball. ... Blazers center Joel Przybilla made his first appearance of the season after sitting out because of a sprained left ankle. ... Raptors rookie Pape Sow returned from left knee tendinitis and made his debut for Toronto.
